71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p>On average, they can exp=
ect their offer to increase. By how much? My clients=E2=80=99 average incre=
ase is 16%, but of course that=E2=80=99s going to be skewed a little higher=
 than the typical person negotiating a job offer. I would guess a typical p=
erson negotiating a typical offer can expect somewhere around a 10% increas=
e in their offer, give or take.</p><p>To give a couple more stats that migh=
t help unpack the =E2=80=9Con average=E2=80=9D part: A little over 90% of t=
he time, my clients see some increase in their offer. A little less than 10=
% of the time, we don=E2=80=99t see an increase, which means the company ac=
tually made their absolute best offer up front.</p><p>Obviously, we negotia=
te hoping to see an increase, but there=E2=80=99s still an upside to negoti=
ating even if it doesn=E2=80=99t yield an increase: By negotiating, you can=
 have peace of mind that you got the absolute best offer and didn=E2=80=99t=
 leave anything on the table.</p><p>Some tactics to explore when negotiatin=
g your job offer:</p><ol><li><p><strong>Ask for a meaningful improvement of=
 10-20% more than their initial offer.</strong><span> Some folks will decid=
e to negotiate, but then ask for a trivial increase, which they will often =
get. But our tendency is to ask for less than we should, which often means =
leaving money on the table.</span></p></li><li><p><strong>Negotiate over em=
ail as long as possible.</strong><span> Recruiters are essentially professi=
onal comp negotiators=E2=80=94they literally do this all day, every day. In=
 a given day or week, your typical recruiter will negotiate more job offers=
 than any non-recruiter individual might negotiate in their entire career. =
So stay in email and off the phone as long as you can. Email also has lots =
of other benefits like giving the candidate a chance to articulate their ca=
se in their own words so anyone in the approval chain gets to see </span><e=
m>their</em><span> case made on their own behalf rather than a recruiter=E2=
=80=99s general summary of it.</span></p></li><li><p><strong>Ask for one th=
ing at a time, starting with the thing you care the most about.</strong><sp=
an> This is in contrast to what I call =E2=80=9Cthe kitchen sink strategy=
=E2=80=9D. That=E2=80=99s where people will ask for lots of things to try t=
o get the most stuff possible, but what that </span><em>actually</em><span>=
 does is gives your recruiter a list of things to choose from when making c=
oncessions, and they=E2=80=99re almost always going to choose the cheapest =
things (which are the least valuable to the candidate). Instead, ask for mo=
re of the thing that=E2=80=99s most valuable and take it from there.</span>=
</p></li></ol><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>How aggressive shoul=
d I be during a negotiation? I am afraid they are going to pull out of the =
process - how should I think about that?</strong><div class=3D"pencraft pc-=
display-flex pc-alignItems-center pc-position-absolute pc-reset header-anch=
or-parent"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-contents pc-reset pubTheme-yiX=
xQA"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-reset header-anchor offset-top" id=3D"=C2=A7=
how-aggressive-should-i-be-during-a-negotiation-i-am-afraid-they-are-going-=
to-pull-out-of-the-process-how-should-i-think-about-that"></div><button cla=
ss=3D"pencraft pc-reset pencraft iconButton2-DvFP7w iconButtonBase-dJGHgN b=
uttonBase-GK1x3M buttonNew-KfJF0Q size_sm-G3LciD priority_secondary-S63h9o"=
 tabindex=3D"0" type=3D"button" data-href=3D"https://nextplayso.substack.co=
m/i/157245945/how-aggressive-should-i-be-during-a-negotiation-i-am-afraid-t=
hey-are-going-to-pull-out-of-the-process-how-should-i-think-about-that"><sv=
g xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=3D"18" height=3D"18" viewBox=
=3D"0 0 24 24" fill=3D"none" stroke=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"2" str=
oke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round" class=3D"lucide lucide-link=
"><path d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"><=
/path><path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.=
71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p><span>In general, there=E2=80=
=99s an aggression range that I recommend staying within: Ask for 10%=E2=80=
=9320% above their initial offer. Where you should be in that range is depe=
ndent on your specific situation, and my general rule of thumb is =E2=80=9C=
The more they need you specifically in this particular role, the more aggre=
ssive you should be.=E2=80=9D</span><br><br><span>I call this your =E2=80=
=9Caggression=E2=80=9D factor, which is basically a number from 0=E2=80=931=
0: higher is more aggressive and indicates they are more eager to get you t=
o accept the job. Take your aggression factor and add that number to 10% an=
d that=E2=80=99s how much to counter.</span></p><p>This is obviously very g=
eneral, but it works well for most people.</p><p>Offers are virtually never=
 rescinded because someone negotiates. I have been doing this for almost 10=
 years, have negotiated hundreds of offers, and I have seen two offers resc=
inded. The last time it happened was over five years ago, and both instance=
s were small firms with in-house HR people who wore multiple hats and didn=
=E2=80=99t really know what they were doing in terms of extending and negot=
iating job offers. Think of a small, local engineering firm with very few e=
mployees and a =E2=80=9CHead of HR=E2=80=9D or something who does everythin=
g from payroll to offer negotiation.</p><p>I=E2=80=99ve never seen a big te=
ch company rescind an offer due to negotiation.</p><p>For most established =
companies with a dedicated recruiting and hiring function, it=E2=80=99s ext=
remely unlikely they=E2=80=99ll pull an offer because you negotiate. Why? A=
 couple reasons:</p><ol><li><p>By extending the offer, they=E2=80=99re sayi=
ng they want you to do the job. They want to make this work.</p></li><li><p=
>The cost to the company to get to the offer stage is substantial. They spe=
nd a lot of time and money to identify, recruit, interview, vet, and offer =
each candidate they hire. They=E2=80=99re unlikely to just waste all of tha=
t time and money in response to a counter offer when they could also just s=
ay, =E2=80=9CAppreciate that you=E2=80=99re asking for more comp, but we=E2=
=80=99ve made our best offer and we hope you=E2=80=99ll accept it.=E2=80=9D=
</p></li></ol><p><span>It=E2=80=99s also important to negotiate </span><em>=
the right way</em><span>. My book and coaching use specific techniques that=
 are designed to be collaborative and get to the best result. I don=E2=80=
=99t recommend using ultimatums, threats, and other hyper-aggressive tactic=
s. If you do wild things in a negotiation, they might decide you=E2=80=99re=
 not the candidate they want to have in their company long-term. But you ha=
ve to push really far outside the normal boundaries to trigger that sort of=
 response.</span></p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>What do you s=
ee as the biggest myths people get wrong about job negotiation?</strong><di=
v class=3D"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-alignItems-center pc-position-absolu=
te pc-reset header-anchor-parent"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-content=
