iv></h3><ol><li><p><strong>They=E2=80=99re not aggressive enough.</strong><=
span> The most common response to the counter offers I suggest for my clien=
ts is, =E2=80=9CWhoa, I never would=E2=80=99ve asked for that much!=E2=80=
=9D If you=E2=80=99re not asking for at least 10%, you=E2=80=99re not askin=
g for enough.</span></p></li><li><p><strong>They ask for too many different=
 things.</strong><span> Earlier, I mentioned =E2=80=9Cthe kitchen sink stra=
tegy=E2=80=9D, which is a common mistake. People feel that by </span><em>as=
king</em><span> for lots of things, they give themselves a good shot at </s=
pan><em>getting</em><span> lots of things, but that=E2=80=99s not how it wo=
rks. Think of your list of possible asks as a prioritized list that you kee=
p based on what you most value in the negotiation. If you offer the entire =
list to a recruiter, they will </span><em>also</em><span> prioritize that l=
ist, but they=E2=80=99ll do it according to the cost of giving you each thi=
ng. Those lists=E2=80=94your prioritized list of asks, and their prioritize=
d list of costs=E2=80=94will usually be inverses of each other. Now the rec=
ruiter can =E2=80=9Cgive=E2=80=9D you two or three things from your list, b=
ut they=E2=80=99re likely to be the two or three </span><em>least</em><span=
> valuable things to you. This makes things awkward because they=E2=80=99ve=
 given you things you asked for, but you probably haven=E2=80=99t actually =
gotten what you want. Instead, ask for the one thing you value the most, se=
e how that goes, then consider asking for the second most valuable thing on=
 your list.</span></p></li><li><p><strong>They share salary expectations up=
 front.</strong><span> Most recruiters will ask you for your salary expecta=
tions and you=E2=80=99ll feel obliged to share that information in order to=
 get your offer. But you don=E2=80=99t have to share that information, and =
it will almost certainly make your negotiation more difficult if you do.</s=
pan></p></li></ol><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>What would you t=
ell a recruiter who asks you: =E2=80=9CWhat is your target compensation?=E2=
=80=9D</strong><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-alignItems-center =
pc-position-absolute pc-reset header-anchor-parent"><div class=3D"pencraft =
pc-display-contents pc-reset pubTheme-yiXxQA"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-res=
et header-anchor offset-top" id=3D"=C2=A7what-would-you-tell-a-recruiter-wh=
o-asks-you-what-is-your-target-compensation"></div><button class=3D"pencraf=
t pc-reset pencraft iconButton2-DvFP7w iconButtonBase-dJGHgN buttonBase-GK1=
x3M buttonNew-KfJF0Q size_sm-G3LciD priority_secondary-S63h9o" tabindex=3D"=
0" type=3D"button" data-href=3D"https://nextplayso.substack.com/i/157245945=
/what-would-you-tell-a-recruiter-who-asks-you-what-is-your-target-compensat=
ion"><svg xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=3D"18" height=3D"18" v=
iewBox=3D"0 0 24 24" fill=3D"none" stroke=3D"currentColor" stroke-width=3D"=
2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round" class=3D"lucide lucid=
