ss=3D"lucide lucide-link"><path d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0=
-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"></path><path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5=
 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p>Think=
 of a target that consists of concentric circles.</p><p><span>The outermost=
 circle is =E2=80=9Cthe industry=E2=80=9D. Look for data points that help y=
ou understand broadly what your skillset and experience are in the industry=
 as a whole. That=E2=80=99s your starting point. Your best source for this =
data is probably a broad search (Google, ChatGPT, etc.).</span><br><br><spa=
n>As you work outside-in, the next (smaller) concentric circle is your mark=
et value in your industry and in your particular geographic region and spec=
ialty. This is more specific, and you can use this data to fine-tune your i=
nitial industry-wide estimate, which was probably pretty broad. Your best s=
ource for data is probably colleagues in the industry, people you=E2=80=99v=
e met at conferences, etc.</span></p><p>The final (smallest) concentric cir=
cle is the specific company you=E2=80=99re going to work for. Sometimes you=
 can find data on what they pay people in your industry, or you might know =
someone who works there or recently worked there who can give you a pretty =
good idea what they pay people with your skillset and experience. With this=
 level of granular data, you should be able to fine-tune your initial estim=
ate even more to get a pretty good sense of your market value. Your best so=
urce of data here is an insider if you can find one.</p><p>At all of these =
layers of abstraction, you may be able to find public data that is somewher=
e between =E2=80=9Ctotally useless=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cpretty darn reliab=
le=E2=80=9D. These sources change a lot over time, but the two that I use m=
ost often are levels.fyi and teamblind.com.</p><p><span>For more on the mar=
ket value estimation process, you can read the =E2=80=9C</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://fearlesssalarynegotiation.com/book/value/" rel=3D"">How to estimate =
your market value</a><span>=E2=80=9D chapter of my book for free.</span></p=
><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>What would you do in a situation =
where a hiring manager low balls you?</strong><div class=3D"pencraft pc-dis=
play-flex pc-alignItems-center pc-position-absolute pc-reset header-anchor-=
parent"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-contents pc-reset pubTheme-yiXxQA=
"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-reset header-anchor offset-top" id=3D"=C2=A7wha=
t-would-you-do-in-a-situation-where-a-hiring-manager-low-balls-you"></div><=
button class=3D"pencraft pc-reset pencraft iconButton2-DvFP7w iconButtonBas=
e-dJGHgN buttonBase-GK1x3M buttonNew-KfJF0Q size_sm-G3LciD priority_seconda=
ry-S63h9o" tabindex=3D"0" type=3D"button" data-href=3D"https://nextplayso.s=
ubstack.com/i/157245945/what-would-you-do-in-a-situation-where-a-hiring-man=
ager-low-balls-you"><svg xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=3D"18" =
height=3D"18" viewBox=3D"0 0 24 24" fill=3D"none" stroke=3D"currentColor" s=
troke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"round" class=
=3D"lucide lucide-link"><path d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7=
.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"></path><path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0=
 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p>First, =
a definition of =E2=80=9Clowball offer=E2=80=9D. For me, a lowball offer is=
 15% or more below your minimum acceptable salary, which is the absolute lo=
west comp you would accept to do this job for this company.</p><p>This is a=
 different type of negotiation because the standard =E2=80=9Cask for 10-20%=
 more than they offered=E2=80=9D strategy probably won=E2=80=99t work.</p><=
p>So instead of just going for a straightforward negotiation, you have to c=
hange tactics and push for a much bigger result. In that case, instead of =
=E2=80=9CYou offered X and I would be more comfortable if we can settle on =
Y=E2=80=9D, you might say, =E2=80=9CYou offered X, which is well below what=
 I was hoping for, and which I found disappointing because of how well alig=
ned I am with this role. I wonder if we can improve the offer so I can cons=
ider it.=E2=80=9D</p><p><span>You might also add a target number =E2=80=9C.=
..I wonder if we can improve the offer to something like Z so that I can co=
nsider it.=E2=80=9D</span><br><br><span>Often, Z will be more than 20% abov=
e their initial offer.</span></p><p><span>This technique can be effective i=
n some cases. One word of caution: If this </span><em>does</em><span> work,=
 then the next offer they make is likely their absolute best offer and ther=
e may not be room for further negotiation.</span></p><p>If this technique d=
oes not yield an offer above your Minimum Acceptable Salary, then you may n=
eed to just invoke that number, =E2=80=9COk, I understand. I=E2=80=99m afra=
id I can=E2=80=99t accept this offer for less than [Minimum Acceptable Sala=
ry], but if we can get there, then I=E2=80=99m on board.=E2=80=9D</p><h3 cl=
ass=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>How do you go about formulating a counte=
r offer?</strong><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-alignItems-cente=
