1a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></but=
ton></div></div></h3><div class=3D"paywall-jump" data-component-name=3D"Pay=
wallToDOM"></div><p>In general, I put equity into two buckets: public stock=
 (RSUs, typically) or private stock options and other forms of private equi=
ty.</p><p>For public stock, I essentially just treat that equity as fungibl=
e with cash (base salary). They=E2=80=99re not technically fungible because=
 the market can shift, and there may be a cliff, etc., but when considering=
 all the pros and cons of =E2=80=9Cequity versus cash=E2=80=9D in this cont=
ext, I=E2=80=99ve found that they basically end up having the same value to=
 my clients. And we end up negotiating for RSUs and cash essentially ambiva=
lently. Whichever one yields more nominal dollars, that=E2=80=99s the one w=
e focus on (unless we=E2=80=99re focusing on total comp).</p><p><span>On th=
e other hand, I usually round the value of private stock options and other =
forms of private equity to zero unless there is some </span><em>really</em>=
<span> compelling reason to not do that.</span></p><p>This is for the purpo=
ses of negotiation, not for the purposes of valuing the company, etc. But o=
nce again, this is a case where we often do a bunch of math to figure out =
=E2=80=9CWhat is this equity actually worth?=E2=80=9D and often end up stru=
ggling and saying, =E2=80=9CNo idea.=E2=80=9D</p><p>It=E2=80=99s a little t=
rite, but I like to say =E2=80=9CYou can=E2=80=99t pay your mortgage with s=
tock options.=E2=80=9D</p><p>That=E2=80=99s not to say that we won=E2=80=99=
t negotiate for stock options, but this usually means that those options tu=
mble down the list of priorities quite a bit and end up being a sort of las=
t resort after we=E2=80=99ve maxed out other, more tangible components of t=
he offer.</p><p>The exception here is if a client specifically wants to max=
imize exposure to the success or failure of a particular company. For examp=
le, I=E2=80=99ve had a number of clients who already had a successful exit =
under their belt, which meant they were more or less financially set, and t=
hey preferred to have as much equity as possible in case the company they w=
ere joining went to the moon.</p><p>A big part of my work with clients is u=
nderstanding what they value, what their priorities are, what they care abo=
ut, and that sort of thing so we can optimize their offer to suit their own=
 priorities. I have opinions, but I am not dogmatic about them and prefer t=
o let my clients drive those decisions.</p><p>Here=E2=80=99s an article on =
how to think about equity when you=E2=80=99re negotiating:</p><p><a href=3D=
"https://fearlesssalarynegotiation.com/negotiate-equity-shares-instead-of-s=
alary/" rel=3D"">How to decide when to negotiate more equity instead of bas=
e salary</a></p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>How would you appr=
oach negotiation when you </strong><em><strong>already</strong></em><strong=
> work at the company? Do you think most people who work in tech are curren=
tly being underpaid or overpaid or about right?</strong><div class=3D"pencr=
aft pc-display-flex pc-alignItems-center pc-position-absolute pc-reset head=
er-anchor-parent"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-contents pc-reset pubTh=
eme-yiXxQA"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-reset header-anchor offset-top" id=3D=
