07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><p>Negotiating when yo=
u already work for a company is a totally different beast than negotiating =
a new job offer. They=E2=80=99re like night and day.</p><p><span>The main d=
ifferences basically boil down to information availability and asymmetry. W=
hen negotiating an offer with a new company, the candidate is at a substant=
ial informational disadvantage, but </span><em>also</em><span> has some key=
 information that the company may not know (namely: their salary requiremen=
ts). This necessitates a strategy that is very guarded on the part of the c=
andidate: The company already has a ton of information that is unavailable =
to the candidate, and the candidate has very little information that is una=
vailable to the company, therefore the candidate should protect that inform=
ation aggressively.</span></p><p>On the other hand, when you already work f=
or a company and you=E2=80=99re negotiating a raise, that information asymm=
etry is much smaller. Because you=E2=80=99re inside the company, you have m=
ore access to, eg, budgets, profitability, recent performance, job opening =
information, hiring trends, and a bunch of other very useful information. A=
nd of course the company already knows what you=E2=80=99re making (because =
they=E2=80=99re the one paying you that salary).</p><p><span>When you=E2=80=
=99re asking for a raise, what you=E2=80=99re essentially saying is somethi=
ng like this:</span><br><br><span>=E2=80=9CMy current salary was set at som=
e time in the past, and my responsibilities at that time were =E2=80=A6 Now=
, I have taken on more responsibilities, which are valuable to the company =
in various ways, and I would like to adjust my compensation to reflect the =
additional value I=E2=80=99m creating for the company since my current comp=
ensation was set.=E2=80=9D</span></p><p>So my philosophy when negotiating a=
 raise is to be as transparent and helpful as possible, ideally giving your=
 manager a proposal they can just rubber-stamp and pass on to the powers th=
at be for approval. You should have a specific target compensation in mind =
(target salary), you should offer justification for that number (your accom=
plishments), and you should help your manager see the value of your contrib=
utions through co-workers=E2=80=99, clients=E2=80=99 and other managers=E2=
=80=99 eyes (accolades).</p><p><span>When you ask for a raise, it should in=
clude all three of those components: target salary, accomplishments, accola=
des. If either your manager is very aware of your work </span><em>or</em><s=
pan> you struggle to come up with accolades, they can be optional, but I th=
ink they=E2=80=99re still very useful.</span></p><p>For accomplishments, qu=
antify the value to the company whenever possible. A handy thing to keep in=
 mind is that companies think of =E2=80=9Cvalue=E2=80=9D in one of three ca=
tegories: more revenue, cost savings, or time savings.</p><p>So think about=
 how your work has made the company more money than anticipated, saved cost=
, or helped move things faster than expected. That=E2=80=99s your justifica=
tion for a raise.</p><p>Once you make your case to your manager in a 1-on-1=
 or other meeting, then you should follow up with a nice, succinct email su=
mmarizing your request along with your justification. That way, your manage=
r can rubber-stamp it, send it along to Finance or whoever owns the budget,=
 and ask them to make the change or consider making the change.</p><p>This =
is obviously hit or miss in terms of result, which relates to the second pa=
rt of this question: In general, I assume that the longer someone works for=
 a company, the more they will look =E2=80=9Cunderpaid=E2=80=9D relative to=
 others working at the company doing similar work. This is not always true,=
 but it=E2=80=99s often true. The best way to resolve this is to change com=
panies so that you can be hired at the market rate for your skillset and ex=
perience rather than being paid your initial salary plus some somewhat arbi=
trary comp increases (raises and merit increases) over a long period of tim=
e.</p><p>For people who are hired into new roles at new companies, I think =
they=E2=80=99re paid about right. It=E2=80=99s a very big market, there is =
much competition, and prices will tend to move to the =E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=
=9D number on their own over time. This is obviously not always true and so=
me folks will be over- or under-valued in isolation, but generally the mark=
et will find the right price to employ people with a particular skillset.</=
p><p><span>For more on how to ask for a raise, you can read the =E2=80=9C</=
span><a href=3D"https://fearlesssalarynegotiation.com/book/raise/" rel=3D""=
>How to get your next raise</a><span>=E2=80=9D chapter of my book for free.=
</span></p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>Switching gears, what h=
as been the biggest unexpected great thing that=E2=80=99s happened after go=
ing independent (as opposed to working for a big company)? On the contrary,=
 what has been perhaps the most unexpectedly bad surprise?</strong><div cla=
