4-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div=
></h3><p>When I started my business, one reason I did that was to sort of p=
rove to myself that I was capable of creating and capturing more value than=
 my day jobs had allowed. I always felt like I was really good at my job, t=
hat I created a ton of value, and that my paycheck did not reflect even a f=
raction of that value.</p><p>Of course, that was frustrating, but it=E2=80=
=99s also easy to say that when someone else (the company) is bearing the b=
urden of all the risk that comes with operating a business. Eventually, a l=
ittle voice in my head said, =E2=80=9CYou think you=E2=80=99re creating so =
much value? Prove it.=E2=80=9D</p><p><span>The actual business I thought I =
was going to start was a B2B SaaS business, and I thought I would just use =
</span><em>Fearless Salary Negotiation</em><span> book sales to support me =
while I built that business. I had written the book as a passion project, b=
ut I also saw its potential and figured I could leverage it as a short-term=
 asset to help me stay afloat while I built my SaaS business.</span></p><p>=
<span>I quickly realized how silly that plan was: Selling enough books and =
related products to pay all my bills every month would </span><em>also</em>=
<span> require me to build a business. So my actual plan had been, =E2=80=
=9CBuild an info-product business to support me while I build my SaaS busin=
ess.=E2=80=9D</span></p><p>I had to choose between the two and, after some =
soul searching, I decided I enjoyed the salary negotiation business more be=
cause it was actually helping people and I liked the work a lot more than t=
he SaaS (which I was just building because that=E2=80=99s what I thought wo=
uld be my best bet to build a sustainable solo business).</p><p><span>You a=
sked about =E2=80=9Cthe biggest unexpected great thing that=E2=80=99s happe=
ned after going independent=E2=80=9D: It=E2=80=99s that I sort of backed my=
 way into building a business where I </span><em>love</em><span> the work I=
 do=E2=80=94I absolutely thrive on helping people capture more of the value=
 they create with their work=E2=80=94and I can clearly quantify and capture=
 part of the value I am creating.</span></p><p>Obviously, I could have done=
 that with the SaaS, but with my salary negotiation business, I can literal=
ly see exactly how much value I create and my fee structure enables me to c=
apture a meaningful part of that value (while still leaving almost all of t=
he created value for my clients).</p><p>So I can look back on that little v=
oice and say, =E2=80=9COk, I think I=E2=80=99ve proved it.=E2=80=9D but tha=
t happened in a totally unexpected way.</p><p><span>The most unexpectedly <=
/span><em>bad</em><span> surprise?</span></p><p>When I began focusing on th=
e salary negotiation business, I initially didn=E2=80=99t have a specific g=
roup in mind in terms of who I would help (a common oversight for new entre=
preneurs).</p><p>I initially wrote the book to be used by pretty much anyon=
e, but the more I gave talks, went on podcasts, worked with people, and oth=
erwise just deployed the methodology, the more I found that Software Engine=
ers just kept showing up as a great group to help.</p><p>I also learned tha=
t finding a niche to serve is a pretty important step for a service busines=
s like I was building. Our intuition is that =E2=80=9Ceveryone=E2=80=9D is =
a lot of people so =E2=80=9Ca business to help everyone=E2=80=9D will be hu=
ge. But it turns out that focusing on a niche and building the business to =
serve that niche can be much, much more effective.</p><p>So I began focusin=
g my business=E2=80=93especially my coaching=E2=80=94on Software Engineers =
and eventually also on Engineering Managers. Even more specific, I found th=
at folks going to Big Tech companies were getting the best results of all m=
y clients. So I began to narrowly focus on =E2=80=9CSenior Software Enginee=
rs and Engineering Managers going to Big Tech companies=E2=80=9D.</p><p>The=
 business grew rapidly as Big Tech started to really soar from around 2018 =
through 2021 or so. Choosing that niche and focusing on it was really payin=
g off!</p><p><span>Until it wasn=E2=80=99t. In the Fall of 2022, all of the=
 Big Tech layoffs started, and my business totally flatlined essentially ov=
ernight. In literally one month, it went from =E2=80=9COh wow, 2021 was gre=
at, but 2022 is on pace to be </span><em>even better</em><span> than 2021!=
=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9CIs my business dead? Now what?=E2=80=9D</span><br><br=
><span>I had not considered that niching down to Big Tech could be risky, b=
ut sure enough it was </span><em>very </em><span>risky. This was a </span><=
em>very</em><span> bad surprise and it took me about two years to rebuild t=
he business after that.</span></p><p>But I learned some very valuable lesso=
ns and those lessons have informed how I decide who to focus on. I had alwa=
ys wanted to continue moving =E2=80=9Cup the org chart=E2=80=9D to help peo=
ple where my expertise could be maximally valuable, but I always envisioned=
 =E2=80=9Corg chart=E2=80=9D to be =E2=80=9CBig Tech org chart=E2=80=9D. Fa=
ll of 2022 helped me realize that focusing on Big Tech could actually be su=
per risky.</p><p><span>Since then, I=E2=80=99ve continued moving up the org=
 chart, but more generally with a focus on =E2=80=9Chigh earners=E2=80=9D, =
who are generally leaders and executives at bigger companies. Those folks <=
/span><em>also</em><span> often work in Big Tech, but not always. And, more=
 importantly, companies will </span><em>always</em><span> need executives a=
nd leaders, regardless of industry.</span></p><p>So while that was an unexp=
ectedly bad surprise that set me on a two-year journey to rebuild the busin=
ess, I think it has ultimately made the business stronger and more resilien=
t, setting me up for longer-term success. We shall see!</p><p><span>Every y=
ear since I started my business, I have written up a Year in Review post on=
 my personal site. You can find them all </span><a href=3D"https://www.josh=
doody.com/category/year-in-review/" rel=3D"">here</a><span>. I=E2=80=99m re=
ally glad I did this because it=E2=80=99s an excellent look at what it=E2=
=80=99s like to build a business from scratch (the highs and the lows).</sp=
an></p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post"><strong>=E2=80=9CI often get Linked=
in messages from recruiters promising me high salaries and bonuses. Should =
I take these seriously?=E2=80=9D</strong><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-=
flex pc-alignItems-center pc-position-absolute pc-reset header-anchor-paren=
t"><div class=3D"pencraft pc-display-contents pc-reset pubTheme-yiXxQA"><di=
