utton" data-href=3D"https://nextplayso.substack.com/i/157245945/i-often-get=
-linkedin-messages-from-recruiters-promising-me-high-salaries-and-bonuses-s=
hould-i-take-these-seriously"><svg xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" wid=
th=3D"18" height=3D"18" viewBox=3D"0 0 24 24" fill=3D"none" stroke=3D"curre=
ntColor" stroke-width=3D"2" stroke-linecap=3D"round" stroke-linejoin=3D"rou=
nd" class=3D"lucide lucide-link"><path d=3D"M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 =
5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71"></path><path d=3D"M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-=
3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71"></path></svg></button></div></div></h3><=
p>Maybe! I have worked with a number of clients who were approached out of =
the blue by a recruiter on LinkedIn. I do think there=E2=80=99s a distincti=
on between an internal recruiter (a recruiter who=E2=80=99s working inside =
a company where they=E2=80=99re trying to fill a specific role that they th=
ink you might be a good fit for) and an external recruiter who might be wor=
king for a staffing firm who is just looking for candidates to include in t=
heir stable of potential candidates to place.</p><p><span>I put </span><em>=
a lot</em><span> more weight on an </span><em>internal</em><span> recruiter=
 reaching out to a candidate about a specific role than I do on an </span><=
em>external</em><span> recruiter who might be making big promises just to g=
et another CV to have available to place if something useful opens up.</spa=
